The Ukraine on the Path to Europe
"East is East and West is West, and never the twain shall meet," Rudyard Kipling once said.
Although Ukraine is undoubtedly in the east, it is in Eastern Europe.
When the country regained its independence ten years ago, European integration became our prevailing goal.
However, the path there was not always paved with success, if it was paved at all.
But the results of the parliamentary elections on March 31 have shown that Ukrainians are still determined to go this way.
I am a Social Democrat and have never been a member of the communist party, although as a lawyer during the Soviet Union I was certainly successful.
It is beyond question for me that our "Soviet" legacy is largely responsible for the difficulties Ukraine faces in joining Europe.
After the collapse of the USSR, the country had an inefficient and militarized industry as well as an unprofessional bureaucratic apparatus.
The huge agricultural areas were practically paralyzed by outdated machine parks and the inertia of state-run agriculture in the Soviet mold.
The rural population sank deep into dirt and poverty.
Low wages make life here very difficult, pensions are a joke, and the shadow economy is enormous.
But our Soviet heritage does not justify everything.
We messed up the reform all by ourselves.
For often we wanted to import proven concepts from the West – private property, free market economy, strict observance of human rights, the creation of civil society, representative democracy – in diluted form and thought that this would somehow help us to preserve socialist elements.
Despite these nostalgic tendencies in politics, the Supreme Council (the Parliament of Ukraine) has over the years adopted laws on citizens' rights and criminal law, family and economic rights, which is akin to a revolution.
The acceptance of Western values in a society that was cut off from European history for centuries was often painful, but has gained momentum, even though we do not necessarily see ourselves as a typical Western nation.
We see ourselves as open, sentimental, friendly, and family-oriented, but also chaotic and indifferent, sometimes irresponsible and lazy.
Still, we are Europeans.
This can be seen on the streets and squares of Kiev.
Today, drivers let pedestrians cross the street, like in Geneva or Munich (while pedestrians in Moscow still have to take refuge from reckless drivers).
In Kiev, there is now a lively café scene and friendly public squares where people can stop and enjoy life.
The young people are learning English, German, and French, they can handle computers and surf the internet in the internet cafés.
But these are only the sentimental wanderings of someone who loves Kiev very much.
The sober eye of the professional politician that I am sees more fundamental changes.
In the last ten years, a development from total rejection of reforms via half-hearted reforms motivated by corruption to a gradual introduction of Western practices has taken place.
The administrative reform reflects this very clearly.
Initially, the reform of the state elicited hostile attitudes among both bureaucrats and ordinary citizens.
A drastic and unconsidered reduction of public servants began.
It was a reform "by template F": the state must shrink, as was assumed, and then the government would run smoothly.
No one considered that countries like France or Switzerland somehow manage to thrive with large state apparatuses.
For the problem is not just a matter of size, but also of organization and efficiency.
The realization that the government is not necessarily improved by simply picking up a red pen led us to the second stage of our reform process.
Gradually, the state was reformed in a more rational manner.
New departments and positions for state secretaries with clearly defined areas of responsibility were established.
Therefore, the work of the ministries stabilized.
At first, the authority granted to these new areas was somewhat too broad to improve their work.
Now they function more or less normally.
Ukrainians may sometimes be annoyed by these impersonal modern mechanisms, but they increasingly accept them as necessary (if grudgingly).
Rational politicians also accept them.
Only Radicals and Populists - of whom we still have far too many - can afford to adopt a indifferent attitude towards a more efficient state.
Taming our Radicals and the radical impulse was not easy.
Why?
Ukraine was for too long a province of the USSR and the tsarist empire, the most important but still a province.
This has shaped our mentality. For radicalism is a byproduct of provincial inferiority complexes.
An overwhelming sense of inferiority and our efforts to deny it have led to some of the most scandalous moments in Ukrainian politics.
The provincial person cannot admit his own inferiority and refuses to learn from others.
To the extent that we shed our provincial inclination to defend ourselves, we open ourselves up to the best that others can offer us.
A century ago, the Ottoman Empire was ridiculed as "the sick man of Europe."
Since 1991, the Ukrainians had to recognize that their country had inherited this sad title in the eyes of many Europeans.
The parliamentary elections held recently have perhaps contributed to making us even more sick, but they have pushed our provincial radicals to the fringes of politics, the communist parties lost their dominant position in the Supreme Council, and the power of the "strong parties" under President Kuchma was significantly reduced.
The reform parties and the European parties have won.
As European outsiders or, at least, as a people on the edge of Europe, we want to build a society in which there are no outsiders or marginal individuals.
As the great and already American writer Vladimir Nabokov said in the 1970s: "Of all the achievements of nature, the most amazing may be the survival of the weakest."
The long, arduous journey to Europe has helped a weak new nation to become strong and survive.
